You are a Java code assistant. Given this Java class: 

package be.objectify.led.factory;

import be.objectify.led.ObjectFactory;
import be.objectify.led.util.StringUtils;
import org.apache.log4j.Logger;

public abstract class AbstractNumberFactory<T> implements ObjectFactory<T> {
  private static final Logger LOGGER = Logger.getLogger(AbstractNumberFactory.class);
  
  public T createObject(String propertyValue) {
    T t = null;
    if (!StringUtils.isEmpty(propertyValue))
      try {
        t = parse(propertyValue);
      } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
        LOGGER.error(String.format("Unable to parse %s to number", new Object[] { propertyValue }), e);
      }  
    return t;
  }
  
  protected abstract T parse(String paramString);
}


write the needed code to perform the migration from log4j to slf4j library. Highlight the code changes needed to adapt the file please.

To migrate from log4j to slf4j in the `AbstractNumberFactory` class, you need to replace the log4j `Logger` with the slf4j `Logger`. Here are the changes needed to adapt the provided class:

### Original Code with log4j
```java
package be.objectify.led.factory;

import be.objectify.led.ObjectFactory;
import be.objectify.led.util.StringUtils;
import org.apache.log4j.Logger;

public abstract class AbstractNumberFactory<T> implements ObjectFactory<T> {
  private static final Logger LOGGER = Logger.getLogger(AbstractNumberFactory.class);
  
  public T createObject(String propertyValue) {
    T t = null;
    if (!StringUtils.isEmpty(propertyValue))
      try {
        t = parse(propertyValue);
      } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
        LOGGER.error(String.format("Unable to parse %s to number", new Object[] { propertyValue }), e);
      }  
    return t;
  }
  
  protected abstract T parse(String paramString);
}
```

### Modified Code with slf4j
```java
package be.objectify.led.factory;

import be.objectify.led.ObjectFactory;
import be.objectify.led.util.StringUtils;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public abstract class AbstractNumberFactory<T> implements ObjectFactory<T> {
  private static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(AbstractNumberFactory.class);
  
  public T createObject(String propertyValue) {
    T t = null;
    if (!StringUtils.isEmpty(propertyValue))
      try {
        t = parse(propertyValue);
      } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
        LOGGER.error(String.format("Unable to parse %s to number", propertyValue), e);
      }  
    return t;
  }
  
  protected abstract T parse(String paramString);
}
```

### Highlighted Changes
1. Import changes:
    ```java
    import org.apache.log4j.Logger;
    ```
    is replaced by:
    ```java
    import org.slf4j.Logger;
    import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
    ```

2. Logger initialization:
    ```java
    private static final Logger LOGGER = Logger.getLogger(AbstractNumberFactory.class);
    ```
    is replaced by:
    ```java
    private static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(AbstractNumberFactory.class);
    ```

3. String.format argument fix:
    ```java
    LOGGER.error(String.format("Unable to parse %s to number", new Object[] { propertyValue }), e);
    ```
    is replaced by:
    ```java
    LOGGER.error(String.format("Unable to parse %s to number", propertyValue), e);
    ```

These changes ensure that the logging mechanism is switched from log4j to slf4j, allowing for a more flexible and widely compatible logging framework.
